Lithos

Volume 100, Issues 1–4, January 2008, Pages 14-48

Geochemical fingerprinting of oceanic basalts with applications to ophiolite classification and the search for Archean oceanic crust

Author links open overlay panel
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.lithos.2007.06.016Get rights and content

Abstract

Two geochemical proxies are particularly important for the identification and classification of oceanic basalts: the Th–Nb proxy for crustal input and hence for demonstrating an oceanic, non-subduction setting; and the Ti–Yb proxy for melting depth and hence for indicating mantle temperature and thickness of the conductive lithosphere. For the Th–Nb proxy, a Th/Yb–Nb/Yb projection demonstrates that almost all oceanic basalts lie within a diagonal MORB–OIB array with a principal axis of dispersion along the array. However, basalts erupted at continental margins and in subduction zones are commonly displaced above the MORB–OIB array and/or belong to suites with principal dispersion axes which are oblique to the array. Modelling of magma–crust interaction quantifies the sensitivity of the Th–Nb proxy to process and to magma and crustal compositions. For the Ti–Yb proxy, the equivalent Ti/Yb–Nb/Yb projection features a discriminant boundary between low Ti/Yb MORB and high Ti/Yb OIB that runs almost parallel to the Nb/Yb axis, reflecting the fact that OIB originate by melting beneath thicker lithosphere and hence by less melting and with residual garnet. In the case of volcanic-rifted margins and oceanic plume–ridge interactions (PRI), where hot mantle flows toward progressively thinner lithosphere (often becoming more depleted in the process), basalts follow diagonal trends from the OIB to the MORB field. Modelling of mantle melting quantifies the sensitivity of the Ti–Nb proxy to mantle potential temperature and lithospheric thickness and hence defines the petrogenetic basis by which magmas plot in the OIB or MORB fields. Oceanic plateau basalts lie mostly in the centre of the MORB part of that field, reflecting a high degree of melting of fertile mantle. Application of the proxies to some examples of MORB ophiolites helps them to be further classified as C (contaminated)-MORB, N (normal)-MORB, E (enriched)-MORB and P (plume)-MORB ophiolites, which may add a useful dimension to ophiolite classification. In the Archean, the hotter magmas, higher crustal geotherms and higher Th contents of contaminants all result in widespread crustal input that is easy to detect geochemically with the Th–Nb proxy. Application of this proxy to Archean greenstones demonstrates that almost all exhibit a crustal component even when reputedly oceanic. This indicates, either that some interpretations need to be re-examined or that intra-oceanic crustal input is important in the Archean making the proxy less effective in distinguishing oceanic from continental settings. The Ti–Yb proxy is not effective for fingerprinting Archean settings because higher mantle potential temperatures mean that lithospheric thickness is no longer the critical variable in determining the presence or absence of residual garnet.

1. Introduction

‘Oceanic Basalts’ are basalts erupted on oceanic lithosphere in non-subduction settings. The methodology for fingerprinting oceanic basalts requires two stages: first, confirmation of their oceanic character by distinguishing them from continental basalts and volcanic arc basalts; and second, sub-dividision of the basalts identified as oceanic into their different intra-oceanic settings (mid-oceanic ridge, ocean island and oceanic plateau).

The geological value in the fingerprinting of oceanic basalts lies not just in reconstructing past oceans. Oceanic basalts carry the best record of how the Earth's mantle evolved, as they are largely free of the complexities created by interactions with sub-continental mantle and continental crust (e.g. Vervoort and Blichert-Toft, 1999, Condie, 2003). Unambiguous identification of oceanic basalts would also help resolve major questions of Earth evolution, such as whether plate tectonics operated throughout the Archean (e.g. Davies, 1992, Hamilton, 1998, Stern, 2005, Witze, 2006). Unfortunately, almost all oceanic lithosphere created before the Jurassic, and a significant proportion of that created since the Jurassic, has been subducted. However, undisputed ophiolites have been documented back at least to the early Proterozoic (e.g. Kusky, 1990, Peltonen et al., 1996, Moores, 2002), and there are many, more debatable ophiolites and related rocks in the Archean (e.g. Moores, 2002; articles in Dilek and Robinson, 2004, and in Kusky, 2004). Fragments of oceanic crust are also preserved as blueschist and eclogite clasts in ultra-high pressure (UHP) terranes back to the Neoproterozoic (e.g. Jahn et al., 2001).

In the early days of understanding magmatic provinces in a tectonic context, fingerprinting oceanic basalts was mainly carried out using triangular diagrams based on immobile elements. Pearce and Cann, 1971, Pearce and Cann, 1973 used Ti–Zr–Y variations to distinguish intra-plate ocean island basalts (OIB) from mid-ocean ridge basalts (MORB) on the basis of their higher Ti/Y and Zr/Y ratios. Wood et al. (1979) used Th–Ta–Hf variations to distinguish oceanic basalts from island arc basalts on the basis of their lower Ta/Th ratios and to distinguish some OIB from MORB on the basis of their higher Th/Hf and Ta/Hf ratios. Wood (1980) also recognised the importance of Th/Ta ratios in detecting crustal contamination in OIB and MORB. Meschede (1986) used Nb–Zr–Y variations to provide a means of separating plume-influenced MORB (‘P-MORB’) from tholeiitic OIB largely on the basis of their lower Zr/Y ratios.

Subsequently, there has been a trend towards using ratio diagrams instead of triangular diagrams as they are easier to plot and model. For example, Pearce (1982) used Th/Yb v Ta/Yb and Pearce and Peate (1995) used Th/Yb v Nb/Yb instead of the Wood projection to fingerprint subduction-related basalts, and Fitton et al. (1997) used Zr/Y v Nb/Y instead of the Meschede projection to separate ‘plume’ from ‘non-plume’ oceanic basalts. A wide range of other projections in immobile element space have also been used in an attempt to better fingerprint oceanic basalts, including Zr/Nb v Nb/Th (Condie, 2005) and Ce/Nb–Th/Nb (Saunders et al., 1988, Kerrich and Xie, 2002). These later methods of fingerprinting also take into account the previously unrecognised diversity in ocean basalts, in particular, the fact that oceanic plateaus make important contributions to oceanic basaltic volcanism.

Despite the availability of this wide range of fingerprinting methods, present methodologies are not entirely satisfactory. First, the separation of oceanic and non-oceanic basalts has not yet formally been carried out using immobile elements. This is important because diagrams geared at fingerprinting oceanic basalts can give misleading results if the basalts are not oceanic, as Wood (1980) demonstrated. Second, the aforementioned plots of Pearce and Cann (separating MORB from OIB), Meschede (separating N-MORB from P-MORB from OIB tholeiites) and Fitton et al. (separating ‘plume’ from ‘non-plume’ basalts) have difficulty dealing with the complexity of oceanic volcanism and the common interactions between plumes and ridges that cause basalt suites to cross discriminant boundaries. This paper develops existing and new methodologies for fingerprinting oceanic basalts in a way that optimises choice of elements and is consistent with present ideas on oceanic basalt petrogenesis. It is based on identifying and utilizing proxies for specific petrogenetic processes. Because of space limitations, it focuses on just two proxies: one for crustal input (and hence subduction, crust–magma interaction, and crustal recycling); and one for melting depth (and hence mantle temperature and lithospheric thickness).

2. Geochemical proxies as the basis for basalt fingerprinting

Geochemical proxies are geochemical parameters which can be used to monitor a chosen physical process. Proxies can usefully be identified and illustrated using MORB-normalized geochemical patterns. Fig. 1a displays MORB-normalized patterns representing the compositional range of oceanic basalt types in the present-day ocean basins: N-MORB, E-MORB, tholeiitic OIB, alkalic OIB, volcanic-rifted margin basalt, oceanic plateau tholeiite and depleted oceanic plateau tholeiite. As the aim is to fingerprint altered rocks, the most mobile elements have been omitted, leaving only the REEs and the HFSEs. To facilitate visualization of the key features, the patterns have been abbreviated slightly by combining (averaging normalized values of) Nb–Ta, Zr–Hf–Sm and Y–Ho so that gradients are continuous from left to right — i.e. there are no ‘plateaus’. In detail, of course, there are important differences in partition coefficients, and hence petrogenetic behaviour, within these groups, but these are not the focus of this paper.

Fig. 1a highlights the negative Nb anomaly characteristic of the volcanic-rifted margin basalt and resulting from magma–crust interaction. To reduce the effects of fractional crystallization and crystal cumulation and highlight the variations at the less incompatible end of the diagram, it can assist visualization to carry out a second normalization to the value of the least incompatible element. The resulting MORB- and Yb-normalized diagram is shown in Fig. 1b for the oceanic basalts only and forms the basis for the Yb-normalized plots used later. Particularly apparent in Fig. 1b, is the negative gradient in the Ti–Yb part of the diagram which characterises the two OIB patterns. This is distinct from the flat patterns for Ti–Yb that characterise both N- and E-MORB compositions. This is the key distinguishing feature between OIB and MORB that forms the basis for discrimination of these magma types on, for example, the Ti–Zr–Y discriminant diagram. Of the oceanic plateau basalts (OPB), the Ontong-Java Plateau tholeiite is intermediate between tholeiitic OIB and MORB, while the depleted tholeiite from Gorgona is distinctive in having a slight positive Ti–Yb gradient. The origin of these variations in Ti/Yb, as is well-known and modelled in detail in Fig. 8, is the presence of residual garnet: Ti and Yb have similar bulk partition coefficients for spinel peridotite assemblages, but Yb is much more strongly partitioned into garnet and hence into garnet-bearing melt residues. Ti/Yb is therefore a proxy for melting depth. In terms of tectonic discrimination, it is a proxy for the combination of lithospheric thickness and mantle temperature which defines tectonic setting and melt production rate, and in turn defines the precise nature of the oceanic volcanic edifice (e.g. McKenzie and O'Nions, 1991).

The second feature is the gradient from Nb to Ti which increases from tholeiitic to alkalic compositions within both MORB and OIB. In contrast, there is little difference between alkalic and tholeiitic compositions for the Ti–Yb parts of the patterns. The Gorgona sample is distinctive in its depletion over the Nb–Ti part of the pattern. The Nb–Ti gradient is a measure of the incompatible element enrichment, or depletion, that cannot be explained by HREE compatibility in garnet. It is mainly a function of degree of melting and composition of the mantle source. For example, the difference between the OIB and the Ontong-Java Plateau tholeiites can be explained mainly by the higher degree of melting of the latter; the difference in Nb–Ti gradients between Gorgona and the other patterns can be explained mainly by the more depleted source of the former.

The MORB- and Ti-normalized patterns in Fig. 1c highlight better the two parts of the geochemical patterns and the significance of the deep-melting proxy. Over the Ti–Yb part of the patterns, the two OIB samples have negative trends indicative of garnet residues, whereas the two MORB samples have flat patterns indicative of garnet-free mantle residues. The oceanic plateau tholeiite, on this basis, has a small residual garnet effect. The Gorgona sample has a positive gradient consistent with re-melting of mantle that had already undergone melting in garnet facies.

To a first approximation, therefore, the variance in basalts represented by the compositional range in Fig. 1 may be divided into three components: 1) crustal contamination for basalts erupted through continental lithosphere giving selective Th and LREE enrichment and hence negative Nb anomalies; 2) source and melting effects giving Nb–Ti gradients, and 3) garnet residue effects giving Ti–Yb gradients. In terms of proxies, the Th–Nb part of the diagram gives a proxy for the crust-derived variance, Nb–Yb gives a proxy for the total mantle/melting-derived variance, which can be divided into Ti–Yb as a proxy for melting depth and Nb–Ti as a proxy for mantle composition and degree of melting.

Expressed numerically, T = X + M + C, where T is the total variance not associated with fractional crystallization, X is the variance caused by mantle composition, M is the variance caused by melting and C is the variance caused by crustal input. M can be divided into variance caused by melting depth, Mz, and variance caused by degree of melting MF so that T = X + Mz + MF + C. Thus T may be represented within any suite of samples by Th–Yb, C by Th–Nb, M by Nb–Yb, Mz by Ti–Yb and (MF + X) by Nb–Ti, where Th–Yb refers to the difference between the Th and Yb MORB-normalized values. These are, it must be emphasised, approximations to the true partitioning of variance, chosen for the purpose of devising simple proxies. Also, although it is convenient to think of, and plot, proxies as ratios (e.g. Th/Nb), they are actually proxies of deviations (Th–Nb). Logarithmic transformations are applied because incompatible elements in basalts have log-normal distributions.

For petrogenetic-based discrimination, ratio plots are easiest to interpret visually if they have common denominators. The approach used here is to focus on Yb-normalized ratios as depicted in the patterns in Fig. 1b and on further development of two plots originally used to study subduction systems (Pearce and Peate, 1995). The first is Th v Nb (i.e. Th/Yb–Nb/Yb) chosen to highlight the crustal contamination proxy; the second is Ti v Nb (i.e. Ti/Yb–Nb/Yb) chosen to highlight the melting depth proxy. These plots, with fields which will be clarified in the next section of this paper, may be seen in Fig. 2.

On the Th/Yb–Nb/Yb diagram (Fig. 2a), present-day MORB and OIB form a diagonal array with average N-MORB, E-MORB and OIB at its centre. Lavas that have interacted with continental crust on ascent, or have a subduction component (Pearce and Peate, 1995), are then displaced to higher Th/Yb values. On the Ti/Yb–Nb/Yb diagram (Fig. 2b), N-MORB, E-MORB and OIB are no longer co-linear. Instead, MORB form an almost horizontal array at a shallow angle with average N-MORB and E-MORB at its centre. Average OIB is displaced to higher Ti/Yb ratios than MORB because of a greater depth of melting. Similarly, the OIB array (made up of ridge-distal islands) is displaced to higher Ti/Yb than the MORB array (made up of plume-distal ridges). Plume–ridge interactions (PRI) follow diagonal trends between the OIB and MORB arrays which will be discussed more fully in the subsequent text.

In addition, alkalic OIB has higher Nb/Yb (for given Ti/Yb) than tholeiitic OIB, and normal (N-type) MORB has higher Nb/Yb (for given Ti/Yb) than enriched (E-type) MORB. The tholeiitic-alkalic dividing line has been constructed using alkalic and tholeiitic Hawaiian basalts according to the original definition using total alkalis and silica of Macdonald and Katsura (1964). The boundary between E- and N-MORB is taken by drawing a line orthogonal to the MORB–OIB array and passing through C1 chondrite so that, essentially, sub-chondritic Nb/Yb ratios classify as N-MORB and supra-chondritic Nb/Yb ratios classify as E-MORB. The diagrams may be applied by using Fig. 2a to determine whether or not the basalts are truly oceanic, and then Fig. 2b to determine the type of oceanic setting.

Note that Fig. 1 demonstrates that there are many other proxies and projections that may achieve the same goals, and the two projections chosen here and the petrogenetic approach discussed here would apply equally to those. There are, however, reasons for the choice made. Th–Nb is the proxy of choice for crustal input because Th and Nb are both immobile from weathering to lower amphibolite facies metamorphism, and because they behave similarly during most petrogenetic processes. La–Nb (or Ce–Nb) achieves the same goal but this ratio also varies in response to partial melting and source composition, so it is more difficult to interpret. Nonetheless, Th may be depleted relative to Nb in certain types of granulitic lower crust while La remains enriched (Rudnick et al., 1985), so detailed examination of the geochemical patterns, and use of diagrams such as La/Nb–Th/Nb that potentially can discriminate different types of contaminant (Neal et al., 2002, Frey et al., 2002), may be important in specific cases.

In addition, Zr is in common use rather than Ti for identifying the setting of known oceanic basalts (e.g. Meschede, 1986, Fitton et al., 1997, Baksi, 2001, Condie, 2005). The advantage in using Zr is that, unlike Ti, it is not necessary to ensure that only basalts are used, so that Fe–Ti oxides were not liquidus phases. The disadvantage for this paper in using Zr/Yb rather than Ti/Yb is that it combines garnet-based and non-garnet-based variance (see Fig. 1) and so, although it contains useful information, is more complicated to interpret and apply. In fact, Baksi (2001) first recognised that applicability of the Nb/Y–Zr/Y projection for distinguishing ‘plume’ and ‘non-plume’ basalts is masked by the garnet-depth effect. Condie (2005) addressed this deficiency by applying it only to tholeiitic basalts, but this paper will show that garnet fractionation affects tholeiites also. There is, in fact, a better case for using Gd/Yb rather than Ti/Yb as it, too, provides a proxy for melting depth and has been used successfully in a number of studies, such as the demonstration of garnet residua in Al-depleted Archean komatiites (e.g. Gruau et al., 1990, Inoue et al., 2000). However, at present, the merits of the equivalent Gd/Yb–Nb/Yb plot have not been fully evaluated.

Note also that it is possible to produce single diagrams that combine the two types of proxy and so carry a greater proportion of the discriminatory power in a single diagram. For example, one could plot Th/Nb v Ti/Yb in order to evaluate crustal input and melting depth in one diagram. In a similar way, Condie's (2005) Th/Nb–Nb/Zr projection combines the crustal input and mantle composition/melting proxies. This approach, while perfectly valid, has not been followed here because the aim of this paper is to focus on projections that evaluate each proxy separately and are most suitable for petrogenetic modelling. For the same reason, discriminant analysis has not been carried out to produce a diagram that carries the maximum amount of discriminatory variance in a single plot (e.g. Pearce and Cann, 1971).

This paper now evaluates the two chosen proxies and their petrogenetic interpretations, in more detail.

3. The Th/Yb–Nb/Yb diagram (Th–Nb crustal input proxy)

The key to the Th/Yb–Nb/Yb diagram is the oceanic basalt (MORB–OIB) array, which contains > 98% of analysed oceanic basalts. Fig. 3 demonstrates the details of variations within this array, using a series of basalts from ocean islands, plume–ridge interactions, plume-distal ridges and oceanic plateaus as examples. This shows most of the samples used to define this array, the additional samples being mainly from ridge segments not in the diagrams for which there are accurate Th and Nb data and some additional oceanic islands. Typically, each region has its own local array within which the more enriched samples, and/or products of lower degrees of melting have the higher ratios, and the more depleted samples, and/or products of higher degrees of partial melting, have the lower ratios. The < 2% of samples that plot outside the array include (a) analytical error, resulting from the typical 2-sigma error of 5% on each ratio, (b) alkalic magmas with a high EM2 (Enriched Mantle 2) component, and (c) a few samples where Th and Nb have been decoupled by processes that may involve interactions with sub-oceanic lithosphere or complex mantle heterogeneities. One would therefore expect oceanic basalts to plot within the oceanic array, except in exceptional cases and where analyses are poor. To reduce the latter, the data used have been checked for Nb–Ta, Th–La and Y–Yb consistency and, where possible, by reference to international standard values.

In detail, ocean islands (Fig. 3a–c) predominantly plot at the high Nb/Yb end of the array, alkalic basalts having higher Nb/Yb than tholeiitic basalts. Although almost all basalts from ocean islands plot within the array, a small subset of alkali basalts from ocean islands is displaced to higher Th/Yb because these contain a recycled crustal component. This is exemplified by the Society Islands in Fig. 3a. As demonstrated elsewhere (see Condie, 2005 and references therein), the EM2 component has a high Th/Nb ratio and HIMU (high μ = high U/Pb) a lower ratio, giving a range of Th/Nb ratios for ocean island basalts. As Th/Nb is a proxy for crustal input, an EM2 component derived from recycled continental sediment (e.g. Hofmann, 1997), would be expected to plot above the MORB–OIB array. It is therefore perhaps surprising that more OIB do not plot in this region. However, any ‘plum pudding’ mantle is a mixture of components (both high Th/Nb and low Th/Nb) and the Society Islands may be rare in being dominated by Th-rich crustal components. Alternatively, the degree of melting may be small enough for the most fusible (continental crustal) ‘plums’ to dominate the melt even when the bulk composition lies within the MORB–OIB array.

Basalts from plume-distal ridges, depicted in Fig. 3d–f for parts of the East Pacific Rise (EPR), Mid-Atlantic Ridge (MAR) and South-East Indian Ridge (SEIR), may be expected to yield data at the lower (depleted) end of the array but it is now becoming apparent from detailed sampling of plume-distal ridge segments (e.g., Niu et al., 1999, Donnelly et al., 2004) that E-MORB compositions are common. In the northern EPR (Fig. 3d), off-axis seamounts (the Lamont Seamounts: Niu et al., 2002) extend along almost the whole array from the highest to lowest Nb/Yb ratios. The northern EPR itself has a smaller dispersion, but almost all compositions have higher Nb/Yb than average N-MORB. The MAR at 10–25°N has an N-MORB average for most ridge segments (Fig. 3e), but some segments (notably around 14°N: Bougault et al., 1988) have E-MORB compositions. The SEIR, in the west, is close to the Amsterdam and Heard Island sites of possible plume-related magmatic activity, but is plume-distal in the east. However, Fig. 3f shows that, even east of 100°E, the SEIR has a significant proportion of E-MORB compositions. Furthest from the plumes, at the Australian-Antarctic Discordance (AAD), the basalts on the ‘Indian’ side of the boundary have an average N-MORB composition, while the basalts on the ‘Pacific’ side are even more depleted than average N-MORB (Kempton et al., 2002).

Basalts from plume-proximal ridges typically form trends extending along the MORB–OIB array away from the plume composition. The Iceland-Reykjanes Ridge system (Fig. 3g) is probably the best-studied example, extending over the full range from alkalic OIB to highly-depleted, MORB-like tholeiites. Other examples rarely achieve the same range, but the trend is typical. Many authors attribute such trends to mixing of enriched and depleted mantle reservoirs (e.g. Schilling, 1973, Fitton et al., 1997, Thirlwall et al., 2004), while a growing number (Phipps Morgan et al., 1995, Phipps Morgan and Morgan, 1999, Niu et al., 1999, Murton et al., 2002, Pearce, 2005) attribute them to loss of melt fractions (pre-conditioning) during the decompression that accompanies asthenospheric flow from an off-axis plume to a ridge. In terms of fingerprinting, the important feature is a wide dispersion of Nb/Yb ratios, with very few samples plotting outside the MORB–OIB array. There is some variation in Th/Nb ratio within the array that may be attributable to mantle domain composition, particularly the relative proportion of the various enriched and depleted components. For example, oceanic islands and ridges from the South Atlantic plot close to the upper boundary of the MORB–OIB array (Fig. 3i) whereas others, such as Easter Island (Fig. 3l) and Iceland (Fig. 3g), plot close to the lower boundary.

Any data set can have rare samples which, because of analytical error or unusual petrogenetic conditions, plot outside the MORB–OIB array. The only set that raises questions about the utility of the fingerprint (this includes other examples not presented here) is Kerguelen and the Ninetyeast Ridge (Fig. 3o), where some 20% of basalts plot just above the upper bound. There is no reason from reported international standard values to believe that these have an analytical explanation. Moreover, unlike the older Kerguelen plume-derived basalts in Fig. 4c, those plotted in Fig. 3o are considered oceanic. Thus either the Kerguelen lavas exhibit the influence of the EM2 mantle component or fragments of continental lithosphere are still participating in their genesis. The latter option provides a reminder that sub-continental plumes that evolve to intra-oceanic plumes may yield a complexity not apparent in purely intra-oceanic plumes.

Oceanic plateaus are less easy to fingerprint because some of the best examples cannot be sampled fully and have a setting of formation that is not well-defined. A number of authors have reviewed the characteristics and identification of oceanic plateaus (e.g. Kerr et al., 2000, Ernst and Buchan, 2003), highlighting flat rare earth patterns and higher-than-MORB Nb/Y ratios as key features. There are no obviously unique geochemical discriminants, however, so identifying oceanic plateaus in the Geologic Record likely requires a combination of geochemistry, geology and dating. This study confirms that oceanic plateaus plot within the MORB–OIB array on the Th–Nb diagram. A further key feature of the Ontong-Java, Caribbean and Colombia plateaus (Fig. 3p–r) is the clusters of data points with Nb/Yb ratios between N-MORB and E-MORB. In addition, there may be enriched samples (as in the Colombia Plateau or on Malaita, the on-land exposure of the Ontong-Java plateau) and depleted samples (as on Gorgona Island in Fig. 3q). Such clustering is much less obvious in areas of plume–ridge interaction, which exhibit a large dispersion in Nb/Yb. The clusters could indicate homogenisation of magma compositions resulting from high degrees of melting, although sampling bias cannot be ruled out as the cause.

Fig. 4 highlights some Th–Nb variations in areas of demonstrable crustal involvement, either direct crustal contamination or crustal recycling by subduction or via inherited subduction components in the lithosphere. The North Atlantic Margin is a type example of a volcanic-rifted margin. The early history may be seen on-land in areas such as the British Tertiary Province (Fig. 4a), but the later history now lies beneath sediment in submarine settings and can be studied only by ocean drilling (Fig. 4b). Both stages provide well-known examples of crustal contamination. The British Tertiary Province, in particular, carries isotope and element signatures of both lower and upper crust indicative of a polybaric plumbing-contamination system (e.g. Thompson et al., 1982, Thompson et al., 1986) and is represented in Fig. 4a by variable displacement from the MORB–OIB array — from undetectable to a ten-fold increase in Th. The transition from rifting to spreading, represented off Greenland by a seaward-dipping reflector sequence, includes more samples within the MORB–OIB array but still a significant proportion with high Th (Fig. 4b). Fitton et al. (2000) summarize how magmas evolved from contaminated pre- and syn-break-up compositions to less uncontaminated or uncontaminated post-break-up compositions. Comparison with Iceland in Fig. 3g, where data plot predominantly within the centre of the MORB–OIB array, demonstrates that the Th–Nb proxy is very sensitive to crustal addition, especially for depleted magmas.

A similar pair of plots that highlights the contrast between a sub-continental and sub-oceanic plume is the India/Antarctic margin (Fig. 4c) and the Kerguelen Archipelago /Ninety-East Ridge (Fig. 3o) which reflect respectively the continental and oceanic evolution of the Kerguelen plume from Cretaceous to Recent. Compared to its oceanic equivalent, the products of the sub-continental plume mostly exhibit Th addition, as well as some possible Th depletion, which might be explained by assimilation of low-Th granulite. The Red Sea margin also exhibits Th depletion and enrichment (Fig. 4d) compared to the truly oceanic parts of the Red Sea and Gulf of Tadjoura (Fig. 3n). Wrangellia, a Triassic plateau exposed along the NW margin of North America (Fig. 4e), may be inferred from its geochemistry and geological setting to have erupted onto arc lithosphere (Lassiter et al., 1995). The vertical vector, marking variable Th addition to magma of otherwise small compositional range, is consistent with this model.

Fig. 4f illustrates the distinction between oceanic basalts and oceanic subduction-related basalts, using the Marianas as an example. As is typical of other systems, the arc and intra-arc rift carries the subduction-mobile Th and is displaced from the MORB–OIB array (Pearce et al., 2005). Back-arc basin basalts (BABB) may lie within the MORB–OIB array if the inflowing mantle is not influenced by the subduction component. With increasing arc proximity, however, compositions are displaced from the MORB–OIB array.

Thus the evidence from all examples in Fig. 4 is that, although basalts erupted through continental crust may not always be displaced from the oceanic MORB–OIB array (contamination-free magma pathways are possible), interaction with crust is extremely common in continental terranes. In particular, suites of basalts (as opposed to single samples) typically exhibit a distinctly steeper vector than that of the MORB–OIB array. Moreover, even if there is no contamination, involvement of sub-continental lithosphere, if it carries a subduction component, could also result in Th-enriched compositions. In consequence, suites of samples displaced from the MORB–OIB array usually do indicate continental crustal involvement via contamination or subduction. Conversely suites of samples plotting entirely within the MORB–OIB array are usually oceanic, especially if their principal axis of dispersion is also parallel to the MORB-OIB array. At the high-Nb end of the array, some alkali basalts may exhibit the effect of recycled crustal components in the mantle source, but the effect is rarely seen at the lower end of the array where the greater degree of melting reduces the influence of these components.

Fig. 5 highlights the petrogenetic rationale for the diagram, focusing on the three main crustal inputs at the present day: subduction, magma–crust interaction (contamination) and crustal recycling. Fig. 5a uses Plank and Langmuir's (1998) compilation of subducted sediment averages from the different subduction systems to demonstrate that subducted sediment lies above the MORB–OIB array — whereas subducted crust lies within the array. In fact, however, the sediment composition is less relevant than the relative mobility of Th and Nb. The subduction addition can then be expressed in terms of two variables: the Th content of the subduction component compared to that in the mantle source; and the ratio of Th to Nb in the subduction component. Fig. 5d demonstrates, using values that allow for some limited Nb mobility, that mantle compositions may be shifted above the MORB–OIB array with little subduction input and that the displacement is greater for the more depleted mantle sources. Virtually all arc magmas thus plot above the MORB–OIB array (Pearce and Peate, 1995), although some back-arc basin lavas can have transitional compositions, as Fig. 4f demonstrated.

Fig. 5b and e examine the effect of crustal contamination. Fig. 5c shows that continental crustal compositions (represented by the upper, middle lower and bulk crust averages of Rudnick and Fountain, 1995) lie above the array. The most fusible crustal compositions (represented by average Phanerozoic and Archean felsic rocks from the same source) lie furthest above the array. The rare exceptions to this are, as already noted, some granulites, which have distinctive Th depletion with respect to the MORB–OIB array, and likely explain some of the differences between lower and upper crust (Rudnick et al., 1985). Primordial mantle lies just above the array, between the crust and mantle compositions that it produced over time. Thus reaction of MORB–OIB magma with continental crust, or recycling of continental crust into the mantle, usually leads to Th enrichment.

Modelling of the diagram depends upon which process of crust–mantle interaction operates for the case chosen. There are four types of model.

  • •

    AFC: assimilation–fractional crystallization (e.g. DePaolo 1981), which is the assimilation of wall rocks assisted by latent heat of crystallization and has the consequence that the most evolved rocks are most contaminated.

  • •

    RAFC: recharge–assimilation–fractional crystallization (e.g. Bohrson and Spera, 2001), which is AFC except that recharge of the magma chamber provides added heat and continually ‘resets’ the magma to more basic compositions.

  • •

    ATA: assimilation during turbulent magma ascent (e.g. Huppert and Sparks, 1985) involves assimilation of the most fusible fraction by the hottest magmas during turbulent ascent.

  • •

    MASH: melting–assimilation–storage–homogenisation (e.g. Hildreth and Moorbath, 1988) has mafic magma entering the base of the crust causing crustal fusion such that an evolved magma of mixed mantle–crustal provenence emerges.

For each process, the precise contamination trajectory depends on variables that include magma composition, contaminant composition, the relative proportion of the magma and contaminant, and the degree of fractional crystallization. Fig. 5e gives an example of a modelled interaction between magma and crust, in which two magmas, one of depleted composition and one of enriched composition, have interacted with Archean felsic crust (A). AFC modelling (DePaolo, 1981) for an arbitrarily-chosen value of r = 0.3 (the rate of assimilation relative to the rate of crystallization) shows that both are displaced to high Th/Nb ratios. Because assimilation is combined with fractional crystallization, and Th and Nb are both more incompatible than Yb, the AFC trends do not converge on the contaminant itself.

Importantly, the depleted magma is displaced much further from the MORB–OIB array for a given crustal input because it has a lower initial concentration of Nb and Th, so a given addition of crustally-derived Th has a proportionally greater effect on the Th/Nb ratio. Variable magma compositions undergoing equivalent contamination will not therefore experience the same deviation from the oceanic array, an effect that is not picked up by plots that utilize only the Th/Nb ratio. On Fig. 5e, it is evident that only a few percent of fractional crystallization, if combined with crustal assimilation with r = 3, is needed to displace the depleted magma compositions above the MORB–OIB array; in contrast, some 15–20% is needed for the enriched magma composition. Note, however, that, even although the composition may not be displaced from the array, the AFC trend may still be detectable from the steep axis of dispersion. The full sensitivity analysis (not shown) demonstrates how these values vary with r, F, crust and mantle compositions, and type of process. One outcome is that OIB is scarcely affected, and hence any alkalic basalts displaced from the MORB–OIB array can usually be explained by recycled crust in the mantle source rather than magma–crust interactions.

The effects of crustal recycling are evaluated in Fig. 5c and f. As noted, the presence of recycled crustal components in the mantle source can affect some alkali basalts. This is evident in Fig. 5c, where average values for alkali basalts dominated by each of the main mantle components (EM1, EM2 and HIMU) have been plotted. EM2 basalts plot on average just above the MORB–OIB array. Of the oceanic island groups plotted for this study, those from the Society Islands are most displaced from the MORB–OIB field, as the compositional field demonstrates. Modelling of crustal recycling in Fig. 5f is used to explain why the displacement found in alkali basalts is rarely evident in tholeiites. The Figure examines the effect of melting a three-component mantle of bulk composition, S: a depleted MORB mantle (DMM) component (which dominates in terms of mass); a crustal component, C, representing an average of the subducted sediments from Fig. 5a; and an alkali basalt vein, V, representing the enrichment component of recycled mantle lithosphere. If the mantle melts homogeneously (DMM, V and C all melt at the same rate), melting trends run parallel to the MORB–OIB array, reflecting the similar bulk partition coefficient for Th and Nb during mantle melting. However, heterogeneous melting, allowing the components to melt at variable rates, gives a melt trajectory in which low degree melts have the highest Th/Nb ratios. The actual trajectory depends on the relative rates of melting of ‘plums’ and matrix. Here the crustal component melts at twice the rate of the vein component and ten times the rate of the matrix.

The reason for the importance of heterogeneous melting in explaining high Th/Nb in some alkali basalts is that C has the lowest melting point and so enters the melt preferentially. The first melt fractions have a high proportion of C, so lie above the MORB–OIB array. They also give a greater dispersion along the MORB–OIB array, not just because of garnet retention in the melt residue which is true of all deep melts, but because the more fusible ‘plums’ also have higher Nb than the matrix. With increased melting, there is less C to melt, and the Nb-rich residues from melting of C may also enter the melt. Therefore, the Th/Nb in the melt decreases with degree of melting. This particular example has a bulk composition above the centre of the array, but any mantle with a mixture of components containing a recycled crustal component can give high Th/Nb in the first melt fractions.

4. Ti/Yb–Nb/Yb projection (Ti–Yb melting depth proxy)

The Nb/Yb-Ti/Yb projection highlights, as noted earlier, depth of melting. The variance on the Ti/Yb axis is almost entirely explicable in terms of garnet residues during melting, while the Nb/Yb axis reflects all source and melting variables other than crustal input.

Fig. 6 gives the plots for the same oceanic basalt suites chosen for Fig. 3. The oceanic islands (Fig. 6a–c) all plot predictably in the OIB field. The alkalic lavas have the highest Ti/Yb and Nb/Yb ratios, the tholeiitic basalts the lowest. Conversely, the three sets of data for plume-distal ridges in Fig. 6d–f plot entirely in the MORB field. The trends run parallel to the field boundary with significant proportions of the datasets plotting as E-MORB. As already noted, the difference between MORB and OIB reflects the fact that OIB, located on thick lithosphere, have garnet residues, whereas MORB, located on thin lithosphere, do not. This simple distinction, however, becomes blurred when one takes plume–ridge interactions into account.

Some potential examples of plume–ridge interaction (PRI) may also follow the trend from N-MORB to E-MORB. This is the case for the Kolbeinsey and Mohn's Ridges (Fig. 6h) and the Red Sea (Fig. 6n). More commonly, however, they trend from the OIB into the MORB field along diagonal arrays, before following the MORB trend at depleted compositions. Iceland and the Reykjanes Ridge (Fig. 6g) exhibit the full diagonal trend from alkalic OIB to N-MORB, as well as a minor trend sub-parallel to this within the OIB field. The Southern MAR (Fig. 6i) also follows a PRI trend from Gough and Tristan da Cunha in the alkalic OIB field to tholeiitic OIB and then into the MORB field, finishing as N-MORB. The South American-Antarctic Ridge (Fig. 6j) is similar but with Bouvet Island as the OIB end-member, as is the Easter Microplate and the North Chile Ridge with Easter Island as the OIB end-member. Galapagos (Fig. 6k) follows a PRI trend but is distinctive in exhibiting two diagonal trends, one within the islands, and one within the Galapagos Spreading Center.

Of the oceanic plateaus, basalts from the Ontong-Java (Fig. 6p) and Columbia plateaus (Fig. 6q) cluster in the centre of the MORB array, at chondritic ratios, though with a small subset within the OIB array. The Caribbean Plateau resembles the PRI examples in its diagonal trend. The main plateau lavas from all three areas cluster around the PM composition, but with slightly higher Ti/Yb ratios. Gorgona Island is distinct in plotting to the far left of the diagram, in the MORB field but more depleted than N-MORB.

There has been much discussion over the high Nb/Y ratios of the most depleted Icelandic basalts (e.g., Fitton et al., 1997), but this plot demonstrates that they likely have the same Nb/Yb as N-MORB. However, Iceland and a number of other plume-proximal ridges do have distinctly lower Ti/Yb than the plume-distal ridges, as depicted on Fig. 2. For example Iceland-Reykjanes Ridge (Fig. 6g), Jan Mayen-Kolbeinsey Ridge (Fig. 6h), Galapagos-GSC (Fig. 6k) and Red Sea (Fig. 6n) all plot in the MORB field but with lower Ti/Yb than N-MORB. This likely reflects the role of remelting of mantle pre-conditioned in garnet facies as discussed later.

This diagram is much less sensitive to crust–magma interaction than the Th–Nb plot. However, some care in needed: average continental crust lies in the centre of the MORB field with felsic rocks beneath the MORB field, so the more contaminated OIB samples will trend towards or into the MORB field. The most rigorous way to use this diagram on such rocks is to choose only those sufficiently unaffected by contamination to still lie within, or just above, the MORB–OIB array on the Th–Nb diagram. For that reason, samples with Th/Nb > 0.2 have not been plotted; fractionated samples with Ti⁎/Ti < 0.85 have also been discounted. Fig. 7 shows the equivalent plots to those in Fig. 4 for the filtered data set. For the North Atlantic, the British Tertiary Province (Fig. 7a) plots predominantly in the OIB field, reflecting its origin during the early stage of continental break-up beneath continental lithosphere which is sufficiently thick to restrict melting predominantly to garnet facies. The North Atlantic Margin (Fig. 7b), which marks the final stages of break-up and hence thinning lithosphere, plots along the PRI trend from the OIB to the MORB field, similar to Iceland in Fig. 6g.

Other margins resemble the North Atlantic in their trend from OIB to MORB with increasing extension. The Indian-Antarctic margin, which marks the Cretaceous break-up of Australia from Antarctica above the Kerguelen plume head, gives a particularly similar trend (Fig. 7c). For the Red Sea Margin (Fig. 6n), the Ethiopia Rift resembles the British Tertiary Province in plotting in the OIB tholeiite field, whereas Afar, where extension is greater, crosses the boundary from the OIB to MORB field (Fig. 7d). The Triassic plateau basalts from Wrangellia (Fig. 7e) plot in a cluster across the OIB-MORB boundary in the PRI field. This is consistent with the interpretation of Lassiter et al. (1995), that the Wrangellia basalts erupted on thicker arc lithosphere, resulting in deeper and less melting than would be expected had they erupted on oceanic lithosphere.

Subduction-influenced samples, as exemplified by Fig. 7f, typically involve MORB-like temperatures and high degrees of fluid-assisted melting which place them in the MORB field. Because Ti, Nb, Yb are usually subduction-immobile, the diagram can reliably be used. Most oceanic arcs plot as plume-distal MORB as in Fig. 6d–f — see Pearce and Peate (1995) for the full volcanic arc array. However, there may be many complexities if viewed in detail. According to the interpretation by Pearce et al. (2005), the mantle entering the Mariana Trough back-arc basin is undepleted and it plots as E-MORB on the diagram. With pre-conditioning during flow, its composition evolves to N-MORB, i.e. Nb/Yb decreases for little change in Ti/Yb. This mantle pre-conditioning is even more apparent during flow to the arc front, with the result that many arc magmas have compositions extending to still lower Nb/Yb than N-MORB. During arc-rifting, incorporation of enriched lithosphere gives increased Nb/Yb in the mantle and leads to the enriched MORB-like compositions on the right of the trend.

An important outcome of this plot is therefore that this diagram is effective, not just for oceanic basalts but also for distinguishing intra-plate basalts (oceanic or continental), which plot in the OIB field from plate margin basalts (ocean ridge and subduction zones) which plot in the MORB field.

The Ti/Yb–Nb/Yb projection can best be interpreted using methodologies developed by McKenzie and Bickle (1988), White and McKenzie (1989), McKenzie and O'Nions (1991), and Watson and McKenzie (1991). They demonstrate that the composition of the erupted basalt for a given mantle source will depend on the depth and height of the melting column which in turn depends on two main factors: mantle temperature, which determines the depth at which melting begins; and the thickness of the conductive lithospheric cap, which determines the depth at which melting ends. To a first approximation: plume-distal ridges have low mantle temperatures and a thin conductive lithospheric cap; plume-distal ocean islands and seamounts have high mantle temperatures and a thick lithospheric cap; and plume-proximal ridges have high mantle temperatures and a thin lithospheric cap. Oceanic plateaus and aseismic ridges, with the greatest melt production rates, require ultra-high temperature mantle and thick lithosphere or high temperature mantle and thin lithosphere. Plume–ridge interactions within the ocean basins and at volcanic-rifted margins result in mantle flow from thicker to thinner lithosphere and so in progressively higher degrees of melting. These scenarios are investigated in the context of the Ti–Yb proxy in Fig. 8.

Modelling of the Ti/Yb–Nb/Yb projection utilizes the method and parameters published by Pearce (2005) for pooled fractional melting over a pressure range of 1 to 6 GPa. The additional Nb and Ti partition coefficients are from the same sources as those cited in that paper and may be found in the caption to Fig. 8. The published method actually models the melting of ‘plum-pudding’ mantle with plums and matrix melting at different rate. In this particular case, the fact that the garnet effect dominates over component compositions (there is no significant difference between alkalic OIB from HIMU-, EM1- and EM2-influenced volcanoes on this projection) allows the mantle to be modelled simply as homogeneous, i.e. using the same equations but allowing plums and matrix to melt at the same rate. Temperature controls the pressure at which melting starts (the temperature–pressure relationship at the solidus is taken from Hirschmann, 2000).

In Fig. 8a, melting trends drawn keeping pressure and temperature constant demonstrate the significance of Ti–Yb as a melting depth proxy. Calculated melting and mantle depletion trends for three pressures: 2.5, 3.0 and 3.5 GPa reveal that shallow melting at 2.5 GPa or below produces little fractionation in Ti/Yb with compositions that stay within the MORB field during melting of DMM or PM compositions. This reflects the similar bulk partition coefficients for Ti and Yb during melting of spinel lherzolite (the slight gradient reflecting the fact that Ti is the slightly more incompatible). At 3.5 GPa, residual garnet leads to extensive fractionation of Ti/Yb ratios at low degrees of melting. Between these pressures, starting at about 2.8 GPa, there is a progressive change from shallow spinel lherzolite to deep garnet spinel lherzolite mineralogies, exemplified by the intermediate trend for 3 GPa. Because partition coefficients decrease with increasing temperature while the proportion of residual garnet increases, magma compositions at 3.5 GPa are similar to those at, say, 5 GPa (not shown).

For each melting trend, there is an equivalent mantle depletion trend representing the melt extraction trajectory of the mantle at the given pressure. Mantle depletion is complementary to melting: Ti/Yb decreases more rapidly in the mantle residue for melting at higher pressure, reflecting the fact that Yb is retained in garnet. The precise depletion trend is difficult to define precisely, because it is dependent on the efficiency of melt extraction and the relative importance of batch melting and fractional melting, i.e. the extent of equilibration between melt and residue. Two examples are shown here, at 2.5 and 3.5 GPa for 2% melt retention. As will be seen, depleted mantle melts in the same way as fertile mantle, giving steep pooled fractional melting trends for deep-melting and shallow trends for shallow melting.

Fig. 8b also highlights the significance of the MORB–OIB boundary. Mantle of potential temperature < 1350 °C will not generate trends that cross the MORB–OIB boundary as the solidus is then intersected at < 2.8 GPa, below the garnet-spinel phase boundary. As mantle potential temperature (and hence depth of the solidus) increases, more melting is needed to produce basalts that lie within the MORB field. For mantle potential temperatures of 1550 °C, comparable to those proposed for the largest Mesozoic–Recent plumes, some 25% melting is needed to generate melts within the MORB field; for depleted mantle, this value is lower by an amount depending on how much melt had been previously extracted. In terms of the MORB–OIB boundary, therefore, samples plotting entirely within the MORB field include MORB itself and oceanic plateaus. Settings with hot mantle and variable lithospheric thickness such as Iceland and Afar form data sets that cross the boundary as lithosphere thickness decreases.

Fig. 8c models the effect of melting mantle that is continuously undergoing depletion by melt extraction as it flows to progressively shallow depth. In this case, the mantle source is no longer fixed but instead moves along a melt extraction trajectory. Mantle far from the ridge axis, which is hotter and melts at greater depth, is then more fertile than mantle beneath the ridge axis, which is cooler and melts at shallow depth. The outcome (illustrated in Fig. 8c for a constant degree of melting) is an initially diagonal trend from OIB to MORB marking a progressive decrease in residual garnet, followed by a sub-horizontal trend within MORB marking garnet-free petrogenesis.

Fig. 8d gives examples, taken from Fig. 3, of fertile mantle (an arbitrarily-chosen primordial mantle composition) of high potential temperature undergoing decompression melting beneath lithosphere of different thicknesses. Basalts erupted on thick lithosphere (exemplified by Hawaii) have the largest Ti/Yb ratios, basalts erupted on thinner lithosphere (exemplified by the Ninety-east Ridge), have intermediate ratios, but also plot in the OIB field. Basalts erupted at or near a mid-ocean ridge (exemplified by the Ontong Java Plateau), experience a high degree of melting and so plot in the MORB field. These compositions all lie on, or close to, the melting trajectory for mantle intersecting the solidus at about 4 GPa. Depleted mantle, still hot enough to melt in garnet facies, gives a melting trend which extends from the melt extraction trajectory for deep, depleted mantle. The data from Gorgona Island are consistent with such a model.

Fig. 8e models the effect of shallow melting. Mantle that loses melt fractions at shallow depth while flowing towards an ocean ridge may be variably depleted. The result is MORB compositions which lie within the upper part of the MORB field, as observed for the Australian-Antarctic Discordance and East Pacific Rise examples from Fig. 3. Note that most E-MORB cannot be explained unless the mantle has an added (low temperature) melt component — as recognised by Donnelly et al. (2004).

Fig. 8f illustrates, using the Easter Island example, the similarity between the theoretical trend for melting of progressively-depleted mantle in Fig. 8c and the diagonal trends observed for plume–ridge interaction in Fig. 3, Fig. 4. This type of model presents an alternative to mixing for explaining the observation in Fig. 3, Fig. 4 that there is an apparent geochemical link between the ridges and nearby oceanic islands (Fig. 3) or continental tholeiites (Fig. 4). Mantle mixing would, however, give a similar result on this projection. Instead of lying on a melt extraction trajectory, mantle would lie on a mixing line between a depleted reservoir of, for example, Depleted MORB Mantle composition and a fertile mantle of, for example, Primordial Mantle composition. Because the depleted source undergoes shallow melting near the ridge and the enriched source undergoes deep melting away from the axis, a diagonal, then horizontal, trajectory would also be the outcome.

5. Applications to post-Archean ‘MORB ophiolites’

Pearce et al. (1984) defined two ophiolite types: MORB ophiolite type and SSZ (supra-subduction zone) type. The MORB-type, as defined, simply implies no subduction component and pre-supposes an origin at a spreading axis. MORB ophiolites could form not only at a mid-ocean ridge but in an incipient ocean, at a plume-influenced ridge, as part of an oceanic plateau, in a back-arc basin some distance behind a subduction zone. The diagrams evaluated here provide a method for confirming an intra-oeanic origin for ophiolites and for resolving further the nature of the oceanic setting. To assess the applicability of these diagrams for subdividing ophiolites, some examples have been plotted in Fig. 9.

5.1. C (crustally-contaminated)-MORB ophiolites

These are ophiolites with crustal signatures that may form in a ridge-subduction setting, the ocean–continent transition zone, and sedimented ridge crests. These can potentially be mistaken for SSZ ophiolites: geological evidence and more detailed geochemical studies (outlined in Table 1) are necessary to distinguish the two.
