The ophiolite suites of the Taitao Peninsula in Chile, formed above a slab-free window by ridge subduction beneath an accretionary complex (e.g. Lagabrielle et al., 1994, Le Moigne et al., 1996), is a type example of this ophiolite type. Dredged offshore samples representative of the subducting Taitao Ridge (Guivel et al., 2003) give compositions from a near-trench setting. For the ophiolite, magma was generated at the subducting ridge by decompression melting, the degree of melting being less than at a mid-ocean ridge because of the thicker overlying lithosphere. The magma rises through the accretionary complex, undergoing combined assimilation and fractional crystallization (Lagabrielle et al., 1994). Shallow ponding of magma with eruption onto the fore-arc sea floor gives an ophiolite-like structure with pillow lavas, dykes, gabbros and peridotites all present.

The key feature in Fig. 9a is that, for the ophiolite, spatially-related samples plot both within the MORB–OIB array and displaced to higher Th/Nb ratios, supporting the Lagabrielle et al. (1994) model of variable crustal contamination. The Taitao Ridge has a similar geochemical composition but has been explained in terms of contamination by a acid magma derived from fusion of hydrated oceanic crust and sediments (Guivel et al., 2003). For either explanation, the composition is not strictly supra-subduction zone type, in that it is not derived from a mantle wedge as in true SSZ ophiolites, but by contamination of MORB. The contamination signature combined with an ophiolite structure indicates a C-type (crustally-contaminated) character. In Fig. 9c, the data plot within the MORB array. Applying a Th/Nb < 2 filter to eliminate samples with major crustal contamination leaves just a few samples, all in the N-MORB field. Thus, the samples may be interpreted as contaminated N-MORB.

5.2. N (normal)-MORB ophiolites

These are defined here as ophiolites which predominantly have compositions which are more depleted than Primitive Mantle. Most, but not all, plume-distal mid-ocean ridges and trench-distal back-arc ridges fall into this category. A good example of an N-MORB ophiolite is the Gabal Gerf complex, which is the largest NeoProterozoic (c. 750 Ma) ophiolite in the Arabian-Nubian shield. It has both trace element and isotope compositions indicative of an N-MORB composition (Zimmer et al., 1995). Using the projections here confirms both the oceanic character (the data plot within the MOB-OIB array on Fig. 9b) and N-MORB character (all but one of the data points plot in the N-MORB field in Fig. 9d.

5.3. E (enriched)-MORB ophiolites

These are defined here as ophiolites which predominantly have compositions which are more enriched than Primitive Mantle. They characterise some plume-distal ridges together with some incipient oceans and some small basins in long transform segments.

Macquarie Island, a Miocene ophiolite representing the crust of the Macquarie Ridge, part of the Australia-Pacific plate boundary north of New Zealand, is a type-example of an E-MORB ophiolite. The boundary at the time of formation was formed by a number of small spreading centres connected by long transform offsets. This is one of the few clear examples of an ophiolite with a E-MORB signature and known tectonic setting (Kamenetsky et al., 2000). The Th–Nb diagram (Fig. 9e) confirms the oceanic setting with compositions that mostly lie between average E-MORB and OIB. The Ti–Nb diagram (Fig. 9g) confirms that the data plot in the E-MORB, rather than OIB, field. Kamenetsky et al. (2000) concluded that the ‘mantle heterogeneity [in the Macquarie island glasses] implicated in this study is not related to the Balleny plume mantle or magmas but is more likely to be regional signature’. The fact that the data plot in the E-MORB field of the Ti–Nb diagram supports their conclusions: plume-proximal ridge settings typically exhibit diagonal trends across the OIB-MORB boundary whereas the cooler plume-distal ridges have near-horizontal trends. The tectonic setting, in which large transform faults separate ridge segments, inhibits mantle flow (and hence mantle depletion by melt extraction) and plate edges cool the mantle. Thus, a petrogenetic model of relatively small degrees of shallow melting indicated by comparing Fig. 9d with the modelling in Fig. 8f is one possible explanation for the E-type character; another is a mantle source that was enriched previously at shallow depth, either during the melting event itself or during the evolution of the mantle reservoir (Donnelly et al., 2004).

A second, particularly important, example is the Jormua ophiolite, dated at c. 1.95 Ga, which is one of many Paleoproterozoic oceanic igneous complexes and one of the oldest undisputed ophiolites (Peltonen et al., 1996). Significantly, it is also the oldest E-MORB, as no proposed Archean ophiolites have this composition. In fact, Peltonen et al. (op.cit.) used Th-Ta systematics similar to those developed here to establish the oceanic origin and identified E-MORB characteristics, which they related to a Red Sea-type oceanic setting. Fig. 9e and g show the equivalent Th–Nb and Ti–Nb which support its E-MORB oceanic character. Figs. 3h and 6h provide a means of direct comparison with the Red Sea analogue proposed by Peltonen et al. The modelling in Fig. 8 supports an origin by shallow melting, either (as discussed for Macquarie Island) involving low degrees of melting, or enrichment by small melt fractions, in a shallow melting environment. The Red Sea basalts vary from compositions more depleted than average N-MORB to E-MORB compositions very similar to those of the Jormua ophiolite. Of course, the larger dispersion of the Red Sea data may result from the fact that they are taken from a much greater area than the ophiolite. Thus, the interpretations made here are consistent with the conclusions of Peltonen et al. (1996).

5.4. P (plume)-MORB ophiolites

These are defined here as ophiolites which predominantly have compositions which cluster around the Primitive Mantle composition on the Ti–Nb proxy diagram and/or form trends indicative of variable garnet influence. They characterise plume-proximal ridges and plateaus.

Type examples of P-MORB ophiolites are the numerous accreted fragments of oceanic terranes that line the Pacific coast of Central America (Hauff et al., 1997, Hauff et al., 2000). Hauff et al. (1997) prefer to term these ‘oceanic igneous terranes’ rather than ‘ophiolites’ though Nicoya and Herradura do at least have plutonic rocks as well as lavas and could fit the ‘incomplete ophiolite’ definition of the Penrose Conference Participants (1972). Fig. 9f shows that data from these complexes lie within the MORB–OIB array, confirming their oceanic character. On the Ti–Nb plot (Fig. 9h), the c. 90 Ma Nicoya and Herradura ‘ophiolites’ occupy the centre of the MORB array. This is also the region occupied by the Ontong-Java Plateau, Caribbean and Columbia data clusters (Fig. 3), interpreted as high degrees of melting of fertile mantle. This matches the interpretation of Hauff and coworkers that they formed from oceanic magmatism at a plume head (the Galapagos plume) and that they represent part of an oceanic plateau, inferred to be the Caribbean Plateau. The younger (66 Ma) Quepos oceanic igeneous terrane lies in the tholeiitic OIB field, consistent with the Hauff et al. interpretation that it is an accreted fragment of an oceanic island chain.

The question then is how the different proxy-defined ophiolite types relate to tectonic setting. As already noted, C-MORB denotes sites of ridge-subduction and, perhaps, ocean–continent transitions. N-MORB may characterise any oceanic ridge. From what we know at present, E-MORB characterises some plume-distal ridges, non-volcanic-rifted margins, spreading segments within transform boundaries and, more rarely, volcanic-rifted margins such as the Red Sea. P-MORB characterises plume–ridge interactions which may include LIPs, plume-proximal ridges and incipient oceans at volcanic-rifted margins.

In terms of other characteristics, SSZ ophiolites and P-MORB ophiolites give the greatest extent of melting, SSZ ophiolites because of subduction-derived water in the mantle source and P-MORB ophiolites because of higher mantle temperatures. This, in turn impacts on the petrology of the ophiolite, reflected in a greater importance of olivine and clinopyroxene in cumulate sequences (such as abundant wehrlites) and a lesser importance of clinopyroxene in mantle tectonite, resulting in more harzburgites. In addition, chrome numbers are higher in chromite and other geochemical proxies (such as Y200 — Y content at 200 ppm Cr) are likely to be low (Pearce et al., 1984).

Table 1 summarizes the MORB-SSZ ophiolite classification extended on the basis of the outcomes of this paper.

6. Applications to the search for Archean oceanic basalts

Although proxies for crustal input and melting depth are key to fingerprinting post-Archean basalts, their applicability to the fingerprinting of Archean rocks is less clear. They are, nonetheless, used extensively to interpret Archean rocks, both in interpreting Nb anomalies and heavy REE depletion in geochemical patterns and in specific projections such as Zr/Nb v Nb/Th (e.g. Condie 2005) and Ce/Nb–Th/Nb (e.g. Kerrich and Xie, 2002) and Zr/Y-Nb/Y (e.g. Baksi, 2001, Condie, 2005). This section aims to evaluate the applicability of the two proxies to the search for Archean oceanic basalts. As explained in earlier sections, the Th/Yb–Nb/Yb and Ti/Yb–Nb/Yb projections have been chosen to highlight the two proxies while minimising other, complicating, variables.

6.1. Application of the Th–Nb proxy to the Archean

There are few Archean basalts which have a tectonic setting that is not debated, and this makes it difficult to evaluate any proxy. However, for the Th–Nb proxy, a useful starting point is Archean basalts and komatiites for which a continental, non-subduction setting may be demonstrated independent of trace elements, i.e. using geology, inherited zircons and isotope systematics. For geological reasons described in detail by Bickle et al. (1994) and geochemical reasons described in the data sources cited in Fig. 10, the best examples include East Pilbara, Belingwe, Northern Superior and the Kalgoorlie-Norseman region of the Yilgarn craton (Fig. 10a–d). The greenstone suites from these provinces form diagonal trends that are steeper than the MORB–OIB array. These trends reflect variable interaction between uncontaminated magmas, which lie within a MORB–OIB array, and crustal compositions, which lie above the array (Fig. 5b). On this basis, the samples least influenced by crust plot in, or just above, the present-day MORB–OIB array. Thus it is evident that the Th–Nb proxy is effective at highlighting Archean crustal input. In fact, it is likely to be more effective in the Archean as magma temperatures and crustal geotherms were likely higher (e.g. Abbott et al., 1994) and felsic crust had higher Th/Nb than present-day felsic rocks (Rudnick et al., 1985).

To test the response of the Th–Nb proxy to Archean subduction, volcanic sequences made up of BADR–adakite–boninite–NEB assemblages (where BADR = basalt–andesite–dacite–rhyolite series and NEB = Nb-enriched basalt) provide the best candidates. Of these, the 3.12 Ga Whundo Group in West Pilbara (Smithies et al., 2005) and the 2.7 Ga Wawa Belt in the Superior province (Polat and Kerrich, 2001) are the best documented and these are plotted in Fig. 10e–f. They are not identical to present-day subduction sequences, an observation attributed by the proponents of a subduction origin to hotter subduction with more common slab melting. However, the data still all plot above the MORB–OIB array, consistent with a selective enrichment of Th relative to Nb in a subduction component. The NEB lavas, which are believed to originate above slab windows, generally have the lowest Th/Nb ratios, although the fact that they lie above the present-day MORB–OIB array probably indicates a non-zero subduction input. Thus, as at the present day, the Th–Nb proxy also provides a means by which Archean basalts with a crustal component introduced by subduction may be distinguished from oceanic basalts.

The second set of examples (Fig. 11) includes Archean basalts and komatiites proposed, some controversially, to lie within the MORB–OIB–OPB (oceanic basalt) spectrum. Arguments for an oceanic origin may be geological or based on the absence of zircon xenocrysts or the ubiquity of juvenile Nd isotope ratios, or a combination of these. It is evident, however, that few of the proposed oceanic greenstones plot entirely within the present-day MORB–OIB array: most have significant proportions of samples with higher Th/Nb ratios. The exceptions are the Kostomuksha greenstone belt in the NW and the Sumozero–Kenozero greenstone belt in the SE of the Baltic shield. Both are characterised by submarine basalt–komatiite sequences containing both pillowed and massive flows and interpreted by Puchtel et al., 1998, Puchtel et al., 1999) as the upper parts of oceanic plateaus. These are the only Archean greenstones (of those plotted) to have unenriched mantle sources and plot almost entirely within the MORB–OIB array in a similar position to basalts from the Ontong-Java Plateau in Fig. 3p. These therefore represent the least controversial candidates for Archean oceanic basalts. The Boston Township samples also lie within the MORB–OIB array, though their more enriched compositions would have made contamination less easy to detect (Fig. 5e). Most other greenstones have a significant proportion of samples above the MORB–OIB array, and/or plotting — on crustal vectors. For these, there are two options: either they are oceanic basalts which experienced oceanic crustal input under Archean tectonothermal conditions; or they should be re-examined in terms of a subduction-related or ensialic setting.

If the first option is valid, Archean oceanic basalts must be able to pick up crustal signals that are much greater than those in their present-day equivalents. There are at least five possibilities: a high Th–Nb Archean MORB–OIB array; Th mobility during high grade metamorphism; crustal recycling; intra-oceanic contamination; and delamination. These are considered in turn below with evaluation of potential examples.

6.1.1. Temporal variations in the MORB–OIB array

As a number of publications have pointed out (e.g. Hofmann et al., 1986, Jochum et al., 1991, Sylvester et al., 1997), primordial mantle has a higher Th/Nb ratio than present-day mantle. During Earth history, primordial mantle separates into crust (with high Th/Nb) and mantle (with lower Th/Nb). If this separation took place in the Hadean, as some have proposed, the Archean MORB–OIB array and present-day MORB–OIB arrays will be similar. However, if crustal growth is progressive (e.g., Jochum et al., 1991), then the earliest Archean MORB–OIB array will be centred about the primordial mantle composition. It will then translate to its present (lower Th/Nb) position over time, so allowing some Archean rocks to plot above the present-day MORB–OIB array.

The c. 3 Ga greenstones of the Regal Formation of the Cleaverville area of West Pilbara (Fig. 11b) provide a test of this possibility as they lie above, and parallel to, the present MORB–OIB array. Ohta et al. (1996) consider these to be oceanic basalts emplaced into an accretionary complex and describe them as Archean MORB (A-MORB). They use this inference to deduce the composition and temperature of the Archean MORB mantle source. Sun and Hickman (1999) revised some of Ohta et al.'s geochemical data (notably Th and Nb) but nonetheless agreed that the rocks had a MORB-like composition, although they raised the possibility of subduction input on the basis of the small negative Nb anomalies.

These negative Nb anomalies are evident in Fig. 11b, where high Th/Nb causes the Cleaverville data to plot above the present-day MORB–OIB array. However, if Archean mantle had experienced little depletion through crustal growth by 3 Ga, the Cleverville data could plot within a 3 Ga MORB–OIB array displaced to higher Th/Nb. The key test of the Ohta et al. (1996) hypothesis is therefore the position of the Archean MORB–OIB array. The latter may be estimated by taking the samples with the least crustal input (lowest Th/Nb) from the various localities plotted in Fig. 10, Fig. 11. Some will be maximum values, as some localities may have no samples that have avoided crustal interaction. Despite this, the result (Fig. 11f) shows that the vast majority of samples plot inside the present-day MORB–OIB array. This includes the oldest greenstones of Isua and Barberton, some of which plot in the centre of the array. Thus, the array does not obviously vary with time. Note that this conclusion is different from that obtained by Jochum et al. (1991), who argued that ‘basalts show a secular increase in Nb/Th because of progressive depletion of the upper mantle complementary to growth of continental crust’. An implication of this work is that magma–crust interactions may have been underestimated in crustal growth studies.

Thus, the finding of this paper is that the MORB–OIB array may be approximately static throughout the rock record and this in turn implies a Hadean episode of crustal growth. This implies that the Cleaverville basalt compositions are unlikely to represent Archean A-MORB as Ohta et al. (1996) proposed. They may have erupted in a supra-subduction zone setting as Sun and Hickman (1999) inferred, or in a continental setting, or have been oceanic but modified by one of the processes described below.

6.1.2. Amphibolite facies metamorphism

Th enrichment relative to Nb may be achieved by high grade metamorphism. Experiments demonstrate that Th is strongly mobilized by melts and weakly mobilized by high temperature aqueous fluids, while Nb is weakly mobilized by melts but not significantly mobilized by aqueous fluids (e.g. Keppler, 1996, Johnson and Plank, 1999). Adakites, with their large negative Nb anomalies, are one manifestation of Th–Nb fractionation by melting of oceanic crust. Empirical studies clearly demonstrate that the volcanic rocks most susceptible to subsolidus Th enrichment are those interlayered with sediments in volcano-sedimentary sequences or mélanges. In such cases, fluids or melts released from sediments can transfer Th via supercritical fluids or melts into coeval and actively metamorphosing metabasalts (e.g. Sorensen and Grossman, 1989). The result is near-vertical displacement of compositions from the MORB–OIB array.

Of the rock suites plotted, the Isua greenstones (Fig. 11c) attained the highest metamorphic grade with peak metamorphism reaching temperatures of c.600 °C for most rocks and > 650 °C in the Garbenschiefer (Dymek et al., 1988). They follow two distinct series, one (in the Central domain) with ultra-depleted Nb/Yb, the other (elsewhere) with Nb/Yb more typical of Archean greenstones. Komiya et al. (2004) interpreted the Isua greenstones as the volcanic component of an accretionary complex, the depleted series representing accreted Archean MORB, and the relatively enriched series represented accreted Archean OIB. This interpretation does not explain why so few samples plot in the MORB–OIB array. Polat et al.'s (2002) interpretation of the ultra-depleted series as boninites formed in a supra-subduction zone setting better fits the steep axis of dispersion of the data, though it does not explain the parallel trend of the second (non-boninite-like) series. A simple comparison with Fig. 10 shows that a continental setting would also fit the data, though Komiya et al. (2004) and Polat et al. (2002) both argue on geological and other grounds against an ensialic origin.

Thus, if the Isua greenstones are to be accepted as oceanic basalts, the steep trend on the Th–Nb proxy diagram has to be explained in the context of an oceanic origin and subsequent metamorphic evolution. Of the possibilities listed here, the magnitude of the displacement and the steepness of the trends makes metamorphism potentially the most viable explanation. Significantly, Frei et al. (2002) and Polat and Hofmann (2003) found that metasomatic fluids rich in Th and other LILE, but not in Nb and other HFSE, probably infiltrated the Isua volcanic sequence. In consequence, Komiya et al. (2004) could be correct in their assertions. A more detailed study would, however, be needed to ‘see through’ any Th metasomatism to evaluate whether the pre-metasomatic compositions would all fall within the MORB–OIB array.

6.1.3. Deep crustal recycling

Fig. 3 shows that a small subset of present-day oceanic basalts plot above the MORB–OIB array as they are derived from mantle containing a component (EM2) of likely recycled crustal origin. This is because Th–Nb is a proxy of crustal input, whether that input is crustal contamination, subduction, alteration by crustal fluids, or crustal recycling.

Kerrich and Xie (2002) used the Th–Nb proxy as part of the Saunders et al. (1988) projection of Ce/Nb v Th/Nb to demonstrate crustal involvement in the genesis of Abitibi plume-related greenstones from the Superior province. Given the absence of any evidence for subduction or Th mobility during metamorphism, crustal contamination is an obvious explanation. However, Kerrich et al. (1999) and Kerrich and Xie (2002) argue convincingly that geological characteristics, juvenile isotope ratios, absence of Si–LILE correlations and absence of inherited zircons all point to an intra-oceanic setting, specifically an ‘aerially extensive oceanic plateau erupted from an anomalously hot super-plume’. Hence they invoke deep recycling of oceanic crust to explain how such intra-oceanic, plume-derived magmas can attain high and variable Th/Nb ratios.

Plotting their data on the Th/Yb–Nb/Yb projection (Fig. 11d) similarly demonstrates the scatter of compositions from the MORB–OIB array towards high Th/Nb ratios. While crustal recycling may be important in the Archean, interpreting the data in this way conflicts with the interpretations made in this paper for post-Archean lavas. Fig. 3 demonstrated that, at the present day, the EM2 component only causes magmas to plot above the MORB–OIB array in a few locations and then predominantly in rocks with high Nb/Yb ratios, i.e. alkali basalts. The interpretation made through modelling (Fig. 5f) is that these rocks are the product of small degrees of heterogeneous partial melting. This enables the most fusible components – the crustal components – to contribute most to the first melts and so impart high Th/Nb ratios. With high degrees of melting, the crustal contribution should be diluted by melting of the less fusible components, some of which may have complementary, low Th/Nb; the result is that tholeiites predominantly plot within the MORB–OIB array.

In the high temperature, sub-oceanic ‘superplume’ envisaged by Kerrich and Xie (2002), the rocks are tholeiitic (and komatiitic) rather than alkalic and degrees of melting are high. That means that the ‘magnifying effect’ of low degrees of melting does not apply. The mass fraction of recycled crust needed to explain the high Th/Nb observed would therefore be greater than anything reported at the present day. Moreover, there would need to be large-scale compositional heterogeneities as many lavas plot in the centre of the MORB–OIB array and so require no recycling. Kerrich and Xie (2002) explain this variability in terms of a zoned plume with entrained crust restricted to its margins. Recycling may be possible on this basis, though there are alternative ways to achieve Th enrichment in an oceanic environment, including that described below.

6.1.4. Contamination within oceanic volcanic edifices

At the present day, oceanic magmas may undergo contamination on ascent, even though the effects are small. Davidson and Bohrson (1998) concluded from a Chapman conference on shallow-level processes in ocean–island magmatism that ‘(1) interaction with the crust is probable or even inevitable on the basis of physical considerations (thermal flux, magma chamber residence to produce differentiates, etc.), although the chemical consequences of such interaction may be subtle to non-existent; and (2) identification of crustal contamination is made easier by the presence of compositionally distinct contaminants (sediments, hydrothermally altered rocks)’. Compared to oceanic volcanic provinces at the present day, Archean magmas were hotter, perhaps up to 300 °C for the equivalent setting (e.g. Nisbet et al., 1993, Abbott et al., 1994), and oceanic crust was correspondingly thicker (e.g. Moores, 2002). This will increase the magma heat power transferred from mantle to crust (e.g. Fowler et al., 2004) and hence increase the potential for crust–magma interaction at deep, as well as shallow, levels. Although bulk assimilation is unlikely to influence Th/Nb ratio (the bulk crust itself lies within the MORB–OIB array), ATA, whereby the country rock releases partial melt as contaminant, will do so: partial fusion of a buried, hydrated basalt should give a contaminant of TTG composition.

The Komati formation of the Barberton greenstone belt highlights the difficulty of assigning tectonic settings to ancient terranes. With access to much the same geological and geochemical information, the greenstones have been interpreted as oceanic crust (De Wit et al., 1987 and subsequent papers), a supra-subduction setting (Parman et al., 1997), a continental or continent-proximal setting (Kröner and Todt, 1988), and an oceanic plateau (Chavagnac, 2004). Fig. 11e shows that a significant proportion of Barberton greenstones plot outside present-day MORB–OIB array, and that data follow a steep diagonal trend beginning in the centre of the MORB–OIB array and extending above it. This trend does not support a subduction origin, as all samples should then lie above the MORB–OIB array. It does, however, imply some crustal input, though the magnitude of this input is less than what would be expected for continental settings given the likely high temperature of Barberton magmas. One option is a continental setting with a high magma flux and hence common contamination-free pathways. An oceanic plateau origin for Barberton (i.e. fully intra-oceanic rather than a detached fragment of volcanic continental margin) may, however, be a better option, provided the Th–Nb trend can be explained in an oceanic context.

As the low Th/Nb end-member from the Barberton trend lies in the centre of the present-day MORB–OIB array, the precise position of the MORB–OIB array is not an issue here. Metamorphism is not sufficiently high grade, and the Th–Nb gradient insufficiently steep, to support Th mobility as an explanation. Deep crustal recycling should not produce such a well-defined trend because mantle containing variable crustal components should also melt to different extents, giving an along-array component of variation. As a result, oceanic crustal contamination is the most promising explanation that would still permit an oceanic origin. Because melt extracted from hydrated, deeply buried basalt potentially has an element composition similar to that of Archean continental (TTG) crust, the resolution of this debate will need high-resolution isotopic studies to establish the age of any contaminant. Such studies to date are limited but favour a continental setting (Wilson and Carlson, 1989).

6.1.5. Delamination and mantle re-fertilization

Bédard (2006) discussed in detail the possibility that greenstones could achieve subduction-like crustal signals by mantle re-fertilization. In his model, similar to that of Zegers and van Keken (2001), thick magmatic sequences build up on static lithosphere and develop a high-density (eclogitic) root. Delamination of this root re-fertilizes the uprising asthenosphere and promotes melting. If re-fertilization by clinopyroxene and garnet involves fusion of delaminated eclogite, then the products could acquire a negative Nb anomaly as well has having juvenile isotope ratios.

Bédard (2006) concludes that ‘re-fertilization of depleted upper mantle sources by delaminated crustal restites has the potential to generate melts with trace element signatures similar to those of Munro-Type komatiites’. He modelled Munro-type compositions by melting a mixture of depleted harzburgite and an eclogite residue from TTG genesis. In Fig. 11d, Munro volcanic rocks occupy a field extending from the centre of the MORB–OIB array to a depleted Nb/Yb, but enriched Th/Yb, composition. Such a trend could signify addition of a constant crustal component to mantle of variable composition. Alternatively, it could indicate a mixture of two compositions, one of depleted mantle with a crustal component, the other an asthenosphere composition that lies within the MORB–OIB array. In either case, a crustal component above the MORB–OIB array is needed. This is not obviously compatible with the addition of crust that has lost a TTG component as Bédard's model requires. However, delamination of a less residual eclogite could potentially explain the trend observed. Note, however, that straightforward crustal contamination of magma is also an explanation for the Munro trend.

Thus examination of Th–Nb patterns in the Archean reveal that, although an Archean MORB–OIB array should be similar to that observed at the present day, surprisingly few Archean basalts plot within this array. This indicates either that few Archean basalts have an oceanic origin, or that the increased heat flow means that contamination is extensive even in oceanic lithosphere, and/or that some other process such as recycling or delamination was more important in the Archean than at the present day. If the oceanic settings are continental and have been misinterpreted, the proxy is correctly informing us about Archean environments; if not, purely uniformitarian application of the Th–Nb proxy, and their equivalents, to the Archean requires caution.

6.2. Application of the Ti–Yb proxy to the Archean

Independent of crustal input, geochemical patterns divide Archean basalts and komatiites into four groups, as Fig. 12 illustrates using MORB- and Ti-normalized patterns. The first and most common, represented by the Munro komatiite, has a flat pattern with no HREE-depletion and is typical of Al-undepleted komatiites (AUK). The second, represented by the Barberton komatiite, has a negative gradient with HREE-depletion and is typical of Al-depleted komatiites (ADK). The third, typified by the Boston Township komatiite, has a steeper negative gradient and characterises Al-depleted and Ti-enriched komatiites. The fourth, represented by the Isua Central domain, has a positive gradient and characterises Ti-depleted komatiites. It is already well-established through experiment that komatiites require high mantle potential temperatures (e.g. Herzberg, 1992, Walter, 1998) and that ADK differs from AUK in having garnet as a crystallizing phase in a magma ocean (e.g. Gruau et al., 1990, Inoue et al., 2000) or as a residual phase from deeper or lower degrees of melting (e.g. McCuaig et al., 1994). It has been proposed that the Ti-enriched lavas represent low degrees of melting at shallow depths, or higher degrees of melting at greater depth, in each case with a garnet residue (e.g. Xie et al., 1995). The Ti-depleted lavas represent remelting of depleted, garnet-rich mantle residues (e.g. Polat et al., 2002). The goal of this section is briefly to address the question of whether the Ti–Yb proxy (and, by implication, the Gd–Yb and Zr–Y proxies) has any relevance to tectonic setting in the Archean. This will establish the extent to which Phanerozoic discriminant diagrams using Y and the HREE may be applied to the Archean.

Fig. 13 carries plots of Archean greenstones from Fig. 10, Fig. 11 on the Ti–Yb proxy diagram. As before, a useful start is to plot the samples known to have a continental setting (Fig. 12a) using, as before, a filter to exclude samples with Th/Nb > 0.2. The continental lavas plotted in Fig. 13a follow a diagonal trend overall. The majority plot in the MORB field between N-MORB and Primitive Mantle compositions, and a subset extends into the OIB field. Fig. 13a also includes the 3.33 Ga Commondale lavas from the Kaapvaal craton (Wilson, 2003) for which no Th concentrations have been published but Nd isotopes demonstrate an ensialic setting (Wilson and Carlson, 1989). Their Ti/Yb ratios (and Nb/Yb ratios) are at an ultra-low level not found in present-day continental settings and require remelting of garnet-bearing mantle residues.

Commondale apart, the overall dispersion is almost identical to that of Phanerozoic volcanic-rifted margins such as the North Atlantic margin (Fig. 7b) and the India–Antarctic margin (Fig. 7c), although a much greater proportion of samples cluster in the MORB field. The difference is that Phanerozoic volcanic-rifted margins extend from OIB compositions on the continents, through transitional compositions on attenuated continental lithosphere, to MORB on thinned continental and young oceanic lithosphere. In the Archean, all the samples in Fig. 13a are continental and (if plates existed) erupted in an intra-plate setting. Most likely, therefore, the higher mantle potential temperatures in the Archean resulted in sufficiently high degrees of melting that lithospheric thickness is no longer the basis of an effective discriminant using Ti and Yb. Some lavas (those in the OIB field) may have experienced less melting, but this is likely to be a function of plume dynamics rather than plate tectonics (e.g. Xie et al., 1995).

The greenstones interpreted as oceanic have been plotted in Fig. 13b–e. The Baltic Shield lavas interpreted as having an oceanic plateau origin (Puchtel et al., 1998, Puchtel et al., 1999) plot in a very similar field to modern equivalents such as the Ontong-Java Plateau. Barberton contains ADK, and hence an origin by melting with residual garnet, which extends the field to higher Ti/Yb, though the data still plot in the MORB field. Isua and S. Abitibi both form diagonal trends extending above and below the present-day MORB array. As with the Commondale lavas, the samples from the Isua Central Domain and Tisdale with ultra-low Ti/Yb require remelting of garnet-bearing mantle residues.

From the modelling perspective (Fig. 13f), high pressure melting trajectories have similar topologies to lower pressure trajectories on this projection. Essentially, the effect of increased stability of garnet at higher pressures, and hence the greater proportion of garnet in mantle residues for a given degree of melting, is balanced by the effect of lower Yb partition coefficients (e.g. Draper et al., 2003). Garnet-melt partition coefficients for Ti, in contrast, do not decrease to an equivalent extent.

At the present day, Fig. 8 demonstrated that the hottest plumes (with Tp of 1550–1600 °C) should intersect the dry mantle solidus at about 4 GPa if they rise adiabatically, and so follow the 4 GPa melting column trajectory in Fig. 12f. Pooled melt fractions from a melting column intersecting the solidus at 4 GPa should initially give compositions in the OIB array, but move into the MORB array after some 2-2.5 GPa of decompression, i.e. beneath a conductive lithosphere some 60 km thick. Thus at the present day, only ridge-proximal plumes give compositions in the MORB field. In the early Archean, mantle potential temperatures of 1550 °C are believed to characterise ocean ridges and produce oceanic crust some 20-25 km thick (e.g. Moores, 2002) and this should lead to sufficient decompression to produce compositions well within the MORB field. By contrast, the hottest Archean plumes, with mantle potential temperatures some 300 °C greater, would intersect the dry mantle solidus at 10 GPa, perhaps more. The melting column trajectory for 10 GPa reaches the MORB field, again after some 2 GPa of decompression but at considerably greater depth. Further decompression, to the base of both thick and thin lithosphere (intra-plate and ridge), will then yield compositions in the centre of the MORB field close to the starting mantle composition. Thus for melting of fertile Archean mantle, the Ti–Yb proxy cannot distinguish between MORB and OIB (or OPB). Archean samples in the OIB field must then reflect plume dynamics rather than plate tectonics (e.g. small degrees of melting at plume margins), as many authors have proposed.

The ultra-depleted samples that lie below the MORB array are particularly interesting. At the present day, no known rocks have such low Ti/Yb ratios (i.e. are derived from such depleted sources) though a small subset of boninites do plot beneath the MORB array. This has led to the uniformitarian interpretation (Polat et al., 2002, Wilson, 2003) that these depleted lavas represent Archean boninites formed in a subduction setting. However, if residual mantle is of higher temperature that at the present day, then water may not be needed for remelting: a second episode of decompression may suffice. Thus, if there were Archean ocean ridges, and if these ridges were fed by still-hot mantle depleted by melting in mantle plumes, then lavas of this composition could be a feature of Archean ridges and Archean oceanic crust could have been a lot thinner than envisaged. This would mean that Komiya et al. (2004) were correct in their interpretation of Isua. However, the Commondale data demonstrate that compositions with ultra-low Ti/Yb were not restricted to oceanic environments. These depleted compositions could, therefore, be characteristic of many settings: continental, subduction or ocean ridge.

It is possible to conclude, therefore, that this diagram and its equivalents have petrogenetic use in interpreting Archean greenstones, but cannot be used to distinguish OIB and MORB, and provide no obvious evidence that plate tectonics took place in the Archean. This means that the Ti–Yb proxy cannot be apply to the Archean as a tectonic discriminant, at least not without more detailed evaluation. The same applies to other mantle depth proxies such as Zr/Y and Gd/Yb, though all are important in interpreting the petrogenesis of Archean magmas.

7. Conclusions

  • 1.

    Fingerprinting oceanic basalts is a two stage process: identifying oceanic as opposed to continental and subduction-related basalts; and subdividing the basalts identified as oceanic into MORB, OIB and OPB.

  • 2.

    MORB-normalized geochemical patterns, double-normalized to – Yb and – Ti to better highlight the less incompatible end of the diagram, demonstrate that the variance in a suite of oceanic basalts may be partitioned into variance derived from crustal input (represented by the Th–Nb part of the pattern), source composition and degree of melting (represented by the Th–Ti part of the pattern), and deep melting (represented by the Ti–Yb part of the pattern).

  • 3.

    Enrichment of Th relative to the equally-incompatible Nb provides a particularly effective proxy of crustal input. On the Th/Yb–Nb/Yb proxy diagram, oceanic basalts plot in a diagonal (MORB–OIB) array. Volcanic arc basalts, with crustal input via subduction, plot in an array displaced to higher Th/Nb ratios. Crustal input via contamination or deep recycling, produces trends oblique to the MORB–OIB array that extend into the volcanic arc array. There remains a small ambiguity because some lower crustal rocks have depleted Th, in which case La additionally needs to be used.

  • 4.

    Modelling the sensitivity of the Th–Nb proxy to crustal addition, indicates how subduction, magma–crust interaction and crustal recycling drive magma compositions out of the MORB–OIB array. For subduction, depleted mantle wedge compositions are most sensitive to fluid and melt addition. Similarly, depleted magmas are most sensitive to crust–magma interactions. In contrast, crustal recycling is most evident in alkali basalts, in part because crustal components in the mantle may preferentially enter the first melt fractions (and so be magnified by small degrees of melting) and in part because alkali basalt magmas are least sensitive to crust–magma interaction.

  • 5.

    Enrichment in Ti relative to garnet-compatible Yb provides a proxy for depth of melting. On the Ti/Yb–Nb/Yb diagram, MORB form a shallow array and basalts with significant residual garnet (i.e. OIB) plot above the array. Products of plume–ridge interactions form diagonal trends from the OIB to the MORB arrays. MORB can be subdivided into N- and E-MORB and OIB can be subdivided into alkalic and tholeiitic compositions.

  • 6.

    Modelling the sensitivity of the Ti–Yb proxy to garnet melting demonstrates that basalts will plot in the OIB, as opposed to MORB, field only if the mantle potential temperature and lithospheric thickness are sufficient to leave significant residual garnet. Thus, at the present day, MORB and near-ridge products of plume–ridge interactions occupy the MORB field whereas most intra-plate magmas occupy the OIB field.

  • 7.

    The proxy-based diagrams work well for Phanerozoic and probably also Proterozoic ophiolites, allowing MORB ophiolites to be subdivided into C (contaminated)-MORB, N (normal)-MORB, E (enriched)-MORB and P (plume-influenced)-MORB sub-types. This may assist subdivision of ridge-type into plume-distal ridges, plume-proximal ridges, ridge-subduction settings, edges of LIPs, incipient oceans at volcanic and non-volcanic-rifted margins and subduction-distal back-arc basins.

  • 8.

    Archean basalts are particularly sensitive to magma–crust interaction because the hotter magmas, the higher Th content of their felsic rocks, the absence of enriched (alkali) basalts, and the apparent absence of low-Th granulites all mean that crustal interaction is usually widespread and easy to detect geochemically with the Th–Nb proxy. Although some 98% of present-day oceanic basalts plot in the MORB–OIB array on a Th–Nb proxy diagram, few Archean greenstone suites, even those proposed on the basis of other criteria to be oceanic, plot entirely within the present-day MORB–OIB array. Thus, either many of these have been misinterpreted as oceanic or Archean oceanic basalts are much more susceptible to crustal input. Displacement of the MORB–OIB array, mobility during metamorphism, crustal recycling, intra-edifice contamination and mantle re-fertilization by delamination all provide opportunities for Archean oceanic basalts to give crust-like signatures. Thus, use of the Th–Nb proxy to define Archean oceanic basalts requires caution at present.

  • 9.

    Although there are notable exceptions, the majority of Archean greenstones, even those with clear continental affinities, have flat MORB-normalized patterns and plot in the MORB array on the Ti–Yb proxy diagram. This is probably because the higher Archean potential temperatures mean that significant residual garnet is rare and not critically dependent on lithospheric thickness as at the present day. Thus the Th–Yb proxy has petrogenetic relevance but tectonic relevance to Archean rocks has yet to be found.

  • 10.

    Like all diagrams used for fingerprinting, there are precautions needed in interpreting basalts of unknown affinities. The question of applicability of present-day proxies to the Archean is discussed above. In addition, for the Ti–Nb projection, it is important to filter out evolved rocks and basalts that have had magnetite on the liquidus; this is best done simply by filtering out any with significant negative Ti anomalies (Ti/Ti⁎ < 0.85). It is also necessary to filter out samples which have experienced significant crustal contamination by plotting only samples with Th/Nb < 0.2. The Th–Nb plot is susceptible to misinterpretation in high grade metamorphic terranes. The Ti–Nb plot is robust for most metamorphic grades but rare instances of metasomatic Yb addition (Larsen et al., 1998) need to be identified, as they may move samples from the OIB array to the MORB array and below.
